ity of Jordan, Amman -- tChapter 12 Referring to Islam in Mutual Teasing: Notes on an Encounter between Two Tanzanian Revivalists -- tChapter 13 Salafis as Shaykhs: Othering the Pious in Cairo -- tChapter 14 Ethics of Care, Politics of Solidarity: Islamic Charitable Organisations in Turkey -- tChapter 15 Making Shari‘a Alive: Court Practice under an Ethnographic Lens -- tChapter 16 Referring to Islam as a Practice: Audiences, Relevancies and Language Games within the Egyptian Parliament -- tChapter 17 Contesting Public Images of ‘Abd al-Halim Mahmud (1910–78): Who is an Authentic Scholar? -- tPart Three. The Ethnography of History -- tChapter 18 Possessed of Documents: Hybrid Laws and Translated Texts in the Hadhrami Diaspora -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPublished in Association with the Institute for the Study of Muslim CivilisationsExplores the impact of the ethnographic method on the representation of Islam in anthropologyGBS_insertPreviewButtonPopup(['ISBN:9780748689842','ISBN:9780748645503','ISBN:9780748645510','ISBN:9780748654796']);This comparative approach to the various uses of the ethnographic method in research about Islam in anthropology and other social sciences is particularly relevant in the current climate. Political discourses and stereotypical media portrayals of Islam as a monolithic civilisation have prevented the emergence of cultural pluralism and individual freedom. Such discourses are countered by the contributors who show the diversity and plurality of Muslim societies and promote a reflection on how the ethnographic method allows the description, representation and analysis of the social and cultural complexity of Muslim societies in the discourse of anthropology.Key FeaturesShows the benefit of using ethnography as a method to engage with and relate to specific empirical realitiesIncludes case studies on rituals and symbols in Syria, Tunisia, Damascus, Algeria, Britain, Pakistan, Brazil and LebanonCovers practices such as veiling, students' religious practices, charitable activities, law, and scholarship in Egypt, Jordan, Turkey and Yemen"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aIslam and civil society. 0aIslamxCustoms and practices. 0aIslamxRituals. 0aMuslim diaspora. 0aMuslimsxEthnic identity. 0aReligious lifexIslam. 0aRites and ceremonieszIslamic countries. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aAishima, Hatsuki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlkan-Zeybek, Hilal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaylocq, Cédric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoissevain, Katia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCantini, Daniele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChagas, Gisele Fonseca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDahlgren, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrici-Bechikh, Akila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDupret, Baudouin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD’hondt, Sigurd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilsenan, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHounet, Yazid Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlaus, Enrique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKreil, Aymon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLange, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPierret, Thomas, 